Nor is Persius less humorous when he refuses to sell his private laugh, mere nothing as it is, for Labeo’s Iliad, or any other man’s, and owns, naively, that though he is not indifferent to praise, he cannot write for it only or chiefly, in times when everything is praised, from the rough heavy work of old Accius to the trifles of men who dictate smooth emptiness as they loll on citron couches, and pronounce the Aeneid inflated and obsolete It would be absurd‚ of course, to attempt to set Persius above Juvenal. We may infer, from the complimentary exhortation put into the mouth of Cornutus (v. vv. 14,15)‚ that it was 'his ambition to found upon Horace a style of reater finish and condensation3 and he corrected himself into obscurity in the attempt His knowledge of life was exceedingly limited, and hence he is constautly enforcing monotonous commonplaces by borrowed illustrations, in which there is nothing fresh, except the shy youthful fervour of the dutiful boy-for he remained a boy to the last, though he was nearly thirty before he died on the Riviera—who describes himself as petulanti splene cachinno, and yet repeats the morose formulae which he had learnt from Cornutus, just as poor Maurice de Guerin repeated the austere ultramontanism of De Lamennais.
